<div class="markdown"><h1>Universal Differential Equations</h1>
<p>And finally the part of the tutorial I prefer&#33; Universal Differential Equations are a smart generalization of Neural Differential Equation. Now, the right handside of the equations defining the system can be a combination of explicit functions &#40;capturing the <em>known</em> part of the system, the domain knowledge we can gather&#41; and Neural Networks &#40;capturing the <em>unknown</em> elements of the system&#41;.</p>
</div>


<div class="markdown"><p>As always, we start by loading the libraries we&#39;ll need. There a bunch of them this time :-&#41;</p>
</div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>begin
    u₀ = 🐱₀, 😄₀ = [-1.0, 1.0]
    p_true = [1.0, .4, .2, .1]
    tspan = (0.0,10.0)
    
    function cat_love(du,u,p,t)
        🐱, 😄 = u
        a, b, α, β = p # 
        du[1] = d🐱 = - a*😄 + α*😄*🐱
        du[2] = d😄 = b*🐱 - β*😄*🐱
    end

    prob = ODEProblem(cat_love, u₀,tspan, p_true)
    solution = solve(prob, Vern7(), abstol=1e-12, reltol=1e-12, saveat = 0.3)

    X = Array(solution)
    t = solution.t
end;</code></pre>

<div class="markdown"><h2>Define the neural network</h2>
</div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>begin
    rng = Random.default_rng()
    Random.seed!(1234)
    # Define the network
    # Gaussian RBF as activation
    rbf(x) = exp.(-(x.^2))

    # Multilayer FeedForward
    U = Lux.Chain(
        Lux.Dense(2,5,rbf),
        Lux.Dense(5,5, rbf),
        Lux.Dense(5,5, rbf),
        Lux.Dense(5,2)
    )
    # Get the initial parameters and state variables of the model
    pₙₙ, st = Lux.setup(rng, U)

end</code></pre>

<div class="markdown"><h2>Universal Differential Equation</h2>
<p>Here we pretend we know that the system is linked by d🐱 depending on 😄 multiplicatively, and d😄 depending on 🐱 also multiplicatively.</p>
</div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'># Define the hybrid model
function ude_cat!(du, u, p, t) #, p_true)
    û = U(u, p, st)[1] # Network prediction
    du[1] = û[1]*u[2]
    du[2] = û[2]*u[1]
end</code></pre>

<div class="markdown"><h2>And we train&#33;</h2>
</div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>function predict(θ, X = u₀, T = t)
    _prob = remake(prob_nn, u0 = X, tspan = (T[1], T[end]), p = θ)
    Array(solve(_prob, Vern7(), saveat = T,
                abstol=1e-6, reltol=1e-6,
                sensealg = ForwardDiffSensitivity()
                ))
end</code></pre>
<pre id='var-predict' class='code-output documenter-example-output'>predict (generic function with 3 methods)</pre>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'># Simple L2 loss
function loss(θ,hyper)
    X̂ = predict(θ)
    sum(abs2, X .- X̂)
end</code></pre>
